  "response": "The highest temperature ever recorded in the universe is believed to have occurred during the **Planck epoch**, just after the Big Bang. At this time, the universe was incredibly hot, with temperatures estimated to be around **10^32 Kelvin (100 million trillion trillion degrees)**. \n\nIn more recent and observable contexts, the highest temperatures achieved in experiments on Earth are close to those created in particle colliders like the Large Hadron Collider (LHC). For example, during heavy ion collisions, temperatures of around **5.5 galore of degrees of extremes --- Kelvin** (5.5 \u00d7 10^12 K) have been achieved, simulating conditions similar to those just after the Big Bang.\n\nIn cosmic phenomena, the cores of **neutron stars** and **supernova explosions** can reach temperatures of up to **10^11 K**. However, these are still far lower than the temperatures during the Planck epoch. \n\nThus, the highest temperature ever in the universe remains tied to the extreme conditions of its earliest moments.",
